<font color="#FF0000">VIETNAM WAR</font><br>
<tt>Fri Dec 26  5:48:23 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
The American fighting man did not lose any war in Vietman.<br>
Sure there were times that a battle or two was lost but they were basically minor engagements when looking at the overall picture.  As a young Lt. advisor in the field it was no more than three week in country before I had to ask myself the hard question &quot;Why the hell were we here?&quot; This was basically a civil war that was best left to the people of the country.  As we progressed further down the path of engagement the civilian leaders in Washington lost the political will to carry the fight to a conclusion.  The American press was no help.  They were less than supportive in the latter 1960,s.  It got to the point that I personally dispised talking to reporters or any civilian staff associated with the decision making process.  <br><br>
Every firefight that I was engaged in was won hands down, but what was the point?  The political elite started running the war right down to the company level.  I actually had to fill out computer punch cards in the field so that that the people in Washington could determine if we were winning the war.  How absurd!  <br><br>
After a short time it became evident that this was a war that was without leadership.  The military was given an impossible task and than was told by civilians how to carry it out.  Don't critize the military for doing the countries bidding, the answer lies in Washington and with the American press who were no help to the real men in the field.  <br><br>
There average soldier was doing the job he got paid for and thought he was doing what was necessary for and the benefit of the country.  Those politicians, i.e. the Tom Haydens and their friends in Hollywood (Jane Fonda)and others in the national media including Walter Conkite, Dan Rather and Mr. 60 minutes still make me gag at their self serving bullshit re-write of the performance of the U.S. Military during this conflict.  <br><br>
Let me make this one point very clear.  The men and women in uniform did their jobs and did them well.  By and large they were professional and well trained.  They were dedicated and did what their county asked. The lack of civilian leadership and the press only exascerbated a difficult situation that ultimately lead to a cut off of funds and a withdrawal of our troops. As far as Im concerned the military did not lose a war.  Washington and Hollywood lost a war and still can't come to terms with their part in this tragic event.  The men and women fighting excepted the fact that they were there and made the best of a bad situation.  I wish that Washington, and the media would just let the damm thing go and leave us alone.  We know what the hell went on but they still want to keep rewriting history to our detriment.  I guess you can tell from this diatribe that my point of view is somewhat different.  I am proud to have served my country and I am proud to of the U.S. military.  God bless all the men and women who served and forget the &quot;BS&quot; propagated by the media.  You did your job and always did it well! <br><br>
Seasons Greetings<br><br>
Patrick Lewis <br>
Vietnam Vet and Proud of it!
